# Django 5 Cursor Rules

## Architecture
- Follow Django's app-based architecture: one app per domain
- Use class-based views (CBVs) for CRUD, function-based views (FBVs) for custom logic
- Keep views thin — business logic in models or service layer
- Use Django REST Framework (DRF) for API endpoints

## Models & ORM
- Use descriptive model names (singular): `Article`, `UserProfile`
- Define `__str__()` and `Meta` class on every model
- Use `select_related()` for ForeignKey, `prefetch_related()` for M2M (avoid N+1)
- Add indexes for frequently queried fields
- Use Django migrations — never modify DB schema manually

## Django REST Framework
- Use `ModelSerializer` for standard CRUD
- Use `viewsets.ModelViewSet` for full CRUD endpoints
- Override `get_queryset()` for filtered queries
- Use `permission_classes` for access control
- Use pagination: `PageNumberPagination` or `CursorPagination`

## Security
- Use Django's built-in CSRF protection
- Use `django.contrib.auth` for authentication
- Never store secrets in `settings.py` — use `django-environ`
- Use `@login_required` / `IsAuthenticated` permission class
- Enable HSTS, secure cookies, and XSS protection in production

## Testing
- Use `TestCase` for DB tests, `SimpleTestCase` for non-DB
- Use `APITestCase` for DRF endpoint tests
- Use factories (factory_boy) over fixtures
- Test permissions and edge cases, not just happy paths
